    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Pardon for Clinton?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Stephen Gillers letter disputes William Safire's August 24 column, which said perjury investigation of Pres Clinton should end with grand jury indictment and pardon, even over president's objection</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (column, Aug. 24) wants the perjury investigation of President Clinton to end with a grand jury indictment and a pardon, even over the president's objection. That's wrong. The grand jury hears only the evidence the prosecutor presents. The accused has no chance to challenge the evidence, submit his own evidence or contest the prosecutor's legal theories. That chance comes at trial.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (column, Aug. 24) wants the perjury investigation of President Clinton to end with a grand jury indictment and a pardon, even over the president's objection. That's wrong. The grand jury hears only the evidence the prosecutor presents. The accused has no chance to challenge the evidence, submit his own evidence or contest the prosecutor's legal theories. That chance comes at trial.</p>
        <p>To use the judicial process for a formal accusation of wrongdoing, and then short-circuit that process before the accused can tell his side, would be a travesty of justice.</p>
        <p>The fair way to achieve closure here is through the report that the independent counsel must file in court. The president and others mentioned in the report will have the right to respond before it is made public.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN GILLERS  New York, Aug. 31, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is vice dean and professor of law at New York University.</p>
      </block>
